<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-164-516  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 164 516.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Datamation  April 1 1989 v35 n7 p97(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Cahners Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IS Operations: the economy's impact on your department.andO;(Information Systems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Franchi, Madeline.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Continuing expansion in the US economy means an even tighter labormarket in the electronic programming community.andP;  Many jobs are notbeing filled as qualified applicants are not available.andO;Employment of computer systems analysts is growing about fourtimes the rate of hiring in other fields, according to the USBureau of Labor Statistics.andP;  Programmers and other computerprofessionals represent the fastest growing occupation in numbersof jobs and growth rate.andP;  The average system programmer and systemanalysts earned in excess of $800 per week during 1987.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ProgrammersHiringRecruitmentEconomicsImpact AnalysisOutlookComputer industry.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablegraph.andO;Caption:   Well-paid programmers and analysts. (table)IS occupations are among the fastest growing. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>IS Operations: The Economy's Impact on Your DepartmentandM;With the start of 1989, the U.S.andP;  entered its seventh year of uninterruptedeconomic growth.andP;  This longest peacetime expansion has moved people from theunemployment line to the assembly line, swelling the ranks of the employed.andM;Just within the period 1985 through 1988, civilian employment climbed to 115million from about 107 million, an increase of 7%.andP;  In 1988, the U.S.andO;unemployment rate averaged just 5.5%, a drop from over 7% in the mid '80s.andO;In some areas of the country, the unemployment rate was even lower.andM;Continued (though slower) economic growth for 1989 and 1990, combined with adecline in the number of entry-level workers, means that the market for laborwill get tight.andP;  For some occupations, and in certain geographic areas, theshortage of both skilled and unskilled workers i already pushing up wages orcausing service cutbacks as job openings go unfilled.andP;  If you are a managermaking staff decisions, you may have already experienced firsthand theeffects of the labor crunch.andM;Of great interest, of course, is the employement and earnings outlook forcomputer and data processing professionals.andP;  In the last several years,employment of computer systems analysts was growing almost four times as fastas total employment.andP;  According to Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS) data,employment of mathematical and computer scientists skyrocketed 28%, to about730 thousand in 1988 from an average of 571.3 thousand persons in 1985, andit's still heading up.andP;  Right now, computer systems analysts make up about45% of that occupational category.andM;Similarly, employment of technicians (excluding health, engineering, andscience) multiplied to about 1,145.3 thousand in 1988 from an average of1,025.5 thousand in 1985.andP;  That was a gain of close to 12%.andP;  Computerprogrammers comprise over 60% of the employment in the technicians' grouping.andM;Computer and data processing professionals are among the fastest growingoccupations, in terms of both the actual number of jobs and the growth rate,based on BLS projections to the year 2000.andP;  By the turn of the century, 251thousand more computer systems analysts and 335 thousand more computerprogrammers will be needed than in 1986.andP;  These gains will be spurred by theever-expanding applications for computers requiring more workers,particularly in the computer and data processing services industry.andM;Results of the 1987 BLS Wage Survey of the computer and data processingindustry revealed that top-level systems analysts and systems programmerswere the highest paid workers in the industry, with average pay generally inexcess of $800 a week.andP;  By metropolitan area, average weekly earnings of alllevels of a systems analysts ranged from about $676 in Washington, D.C., upto $860 in and around San Jose.andO;</TEXT></DOC>